meta_friction: Signal capture is append-only but processing verification is binary (has-ref / no-ref) with no measurement of whether the named artifacts actually produced downstream improvement, creating a gap between documentation completeness (100%) and demonstrated impact (40%).
key_findings: All 50 signals have artifact refs (100% enforcement completeness), but this measures documentation fidelity, not causal impact — the two are not the same quality gate.

Signal sessions above baseline cluster in two bursts: S178-S182 (change_quality + expect-diff + self-improvement signals) and S186-S189 (domain expansion + autonomy signals), suggesting signals work best when they target swarm-internal methodology rather than just adding scope.

Domain expansion is the largest signal category (19/50 = 38%) and contributed 31 domains, but the per-session quality score does not persistently rise after domain signals — domains are opened faster than they are swarmed (L-284: 1.5% throughput; 204 lanes, 3 closed).

S186 contributed 21 signals in a single session (42% of all signals), creating a processing overhang: the SWARM-LANES bloat ratio hit 2.0x (L-304) and long-term quality trend declined -23% from the early average.

The most impactful signal category by downstream quality is self_improvement (S178, S181, S182 all STRONG), confirming PHIL-4: signals about improving swarm methodology yield measurably higher-quality sessions than signals about expanding scope.
